{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500898"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:19:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:19:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1694"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1694"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.15,0.58,0.14,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1694"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116339"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1694"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1694"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98335"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2697"},{"type":"tags","id":"2765"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"7861"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1792"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1951"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16219"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17433"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36621"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42369"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45911"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45912"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116339"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department of a metropolitan hospital with acute onset of dull central chest pain for 20 minutes, accompanied by diaphoresis and light-headedness. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, the patient\u0027s hands are cool and clammy, her blood pressure is 86/54 mmHg, her oxygen saturation is 95% on room air, chest is clear on auscultation, and her respiratory rate is 23 breaths/minute. Her ECG is shown here (image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["High flow oxygen","Thrombolysis","Cautious intravenous fluid bolus","Nitroglycerin","IV Morphine"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and ECG findings consistent with an ST-segment elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI). The clinical presentation of a dull central chest pain, with associated ST elevation on ECG, is supportive of a STEMI. The ECG abnormalities include ST-segment elevation in the anterior leads, which indicates acute myocardial injury in the anterior wall of the heart. The patient\u0027s hypotension, pallor, and tachypnoea suggest she may be in a state of cardiogenic shock, a condition that can occur in myocardial infarction patients due to severe impairment of cardiac function. Clinical signs of cardiogenic shock include hypotension, tachycardia, altered mental status, and cool, clammy skin. Management involves stabilising the patient with intravenous fluids to improve perfusion and support blood pressure, alongside definitive revascularisation therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous fluid bolus\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management. In the setting of hypotension and potential cardiogenic shock, a cautious fluid bolus can help improve preload and cardiac output, thereby stabilising the patient\u0027s haemodynamics. Administering fluids can help support blood pressure and improve perfusion, which is critical before definitive treatment like PCI. This is particularly important before considering other interventions that may further reduce blood pressure, such as nitroglycerin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh flow oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as the patient\u0027s oxygen saturation is 95% on room air, which is adequate. Guidelines recommend oxygen only if the saturations are less than 94%, and routine use of high flow oxygen in myocardial infarction without hypoxia is not recommended as it may lead to adverse outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrombolysis\u003C/strong\u003E is a treatment option for myocardial infarction, particularly when percutaneous coronary intervention is not available. However, it is not the immediate next step in this scenario, where stabilisation of the patient\u0027s haemodynamics is the priority and they are in a major tertiary centre where PCI is available. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENitroglycerin\u003C/strong\u003E is typically used to relieve chest pain in myocardial infarction by dilating coronary arteries. However, it can cause hypotension, which is contraindicated in this patient who is already hypotensive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV Morphine\u003C/strong\u003E is used for pain relief in myocardial infarction but can also cause hypotension and should be used cautiously, especially in patients with signs of shock. Fentanyl is another short acting opioid alternative that has less effect on blood pressure however the immediate priority is to address the hypotension and improve tissue perfusion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Percutaneous coronary intervention should always be considered in those who present early after a myocardial infarction.","Initial management of myocardial infarction includes stabilisation of the patient, often with oxygen and intravenous fluids.","Cardiogenic shock is a condition that can occur in myocardial infarction patients due to severe impairment of cardiac function, and clinical signs include hypotension, tachycardia, altered mental status, and cool, clammy skin."],"references":["Ahmad M, Mehta P, Reddivari AKR, et al. Percutaneous Coronary Intervention. [Updated 2021 Jan 16]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021 Jan. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK556123/?report=classic","French J. STEMI \u2013 a medical emergency. Medicine Today[Internet]. 2014; 15(1): 12-17. Available from: https://medicinetoday.com.au/system/files/pdf/medicine_today/article/MT2014-01-012-FRENCH.pdf","Shaikh AH, Siddiqui MS, Hanif B, Malik F, Hasan K, Adhi F. Outcomes of primary percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI) in a tertiary care cardiac centre. J Pak Med Assoc. 2009 Jul;59(7):426-9. PMID: 19579726.","Vahdatpour C, Collins D, Goldberg S. Cardiogenic Shock. J Am Heart Assoc. 2019 Apr 16;8(8):e011991. doi: 10.1161/JAHA.119.011991. PMID: 30947630; PMCID: PMC6507212.","Laghlam D, Benghanem S, Ortuno S, Bouabdallaoui N, Manzo-Silberman S, Hamzaoui O, Aissaoui N. Management of cardiogenic shock: a narrative review. Ann Intensive Care. 2024 Mar 30;14(1):45. doi: 10.1186/s13613-024-01260-y. PMID: 38553663; PMCID: PMC10980676."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98335"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1694"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19305"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19305"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media